irate' Movie Streaming Site Fmovies Sued in US Court|date=2016-10-26|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/us-court-orders-pirate-streaming-site-fmovies-to-pay-210000-170609/|title=US Court Orders Pirate Streaming Site FMovies to Pay $210,000|date=2017-06-09|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe site was created sometime in 2016 according to ''[[TorrentFreak]],''<ref name=\":2\" /> and blocked from [[Google]] searches in December 2016.\n\nIn October 2017, FMovies lost a lawsuit brought by Filipino media and entertainment group [[ABS-CBN]], and was ordered to pay $210,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/abs-cbn-wants-210000-piracy-damages-from-fmovies-170401/|title=ABS-CBN Wants $210,000 Piracy Damages From FMovies|date=2017-04-01|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fossbytes.com/fmovies-shutdown-possible-court-domain-lawsuit/|title=Will FMovies Soon Lose Its Domain Name? Court Orders The Site To Pay $210,000|last=Verma|first=Adarsh|date=2017-06-10|website=Fossbytes|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mobipicker.com/fmovies-copyright-lawsuit/|title=FMovies.to and FMovies.se to Shut Down Soon? US Court Orders To Pay $210,000 In Copyright Infringement Lawsuit|last=Sharma|first=Shubham|date=2017-06-11|website=MobiPicker|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, the site was identified as a ''Notorious Market'' by the U.S. government, along with [[The Pirate Bay]] and other piracy sites.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/us-govt-brands-torrent-streaming-cyberlocker-sites-as-notorious-markets-180115/|title=US Govt Brands Torrent, Streaming & Cyberlocker Sites As Notorious Markets|date=2018-01-15|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, [[Telia Company]], a Swedish ISP, was ordered to block FMovies.<ref name=\":0\" /> They appealed the order.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/swedish-isp-telia-appeals-pirate-bay-blocking-order-181026/|title=Swedish ISP Telia Appeals Pirate Bay Blocking Order|date=2018-10-26|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>  That same month, the [[Motion Picture Association of America]] reported FMovies along with other piracy sites to the U.S. government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/mpaa-reports-notorious-piracy-threats-to-the-us-government-181003/|title=MPAA Reports 'Notorious' Pirate Sites to The US Government|date=2018-10-03|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nFMovies was blocked in Australia in December 2018, after a request in August.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/australian-court-orders-blocking-of-subtitle-piracy-sites/|title=Australian court orders blocking of subtitle piracy sites|last=Barbaschow|first=Asha|website=ZDNet|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/australian-court-orders-isps-to-block-181-pirate-domains-including-subtitle-sites-181220/|title=Australian Court Orders ISPs to Block 181 'Pirate' Domains, Including Subtitle Sites|date=2018-12-20|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/movie-tv-show-companies-want-subtitle-sites-blocked-down-under-180802/|title=Movie & TV Show Companies Want Subtitle Sites Blocked Down Under|date=2018-08-02|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, Sweden asked advertisers to blacklist some piracy and streaming sites, which included FMovies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/sweden-asks-advertisers-to-blacklist-streaming-and-torrent-sites-190223/|title=Sweden Asks Advertisers to Blacklist Streaming and Torrent Sites|date=2019-02-23|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techdoctoruk.com/tech-news/sweden-asks-advertisers-to-blacklist-streaming-and-torrent-sites/|title=Sweden Asks Advertisers to Blacklist Streaming and Torrent Sites \u2013 TechDoctorUK|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://letscrackon.org/sweden-asks-advertisers-to-blacklist-streaming-and-torrent-sites/|title=Sweden Asks Advertisers to Blacklist Streaming and Torrent Sites|last=Tech|first=Free|date=2019-02-23|website=Let's Crack On|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.docsquiffy.com/2019/02/23/sweden-asks-advertisers-to-blacklist-streaming-and-torrent-sites/|title=Sweden Asks Advertisers to Blacklist Streaming and Torrent Sites|last=Squiffy|first=Doc|date=2019-02-23|website=DocSquiffy.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-05-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190525142255/https://www.docsquiffy.com/2019/02/23/sweden-asks-advertisers-to-blacklist-streaming-and-torrent-sites/|archive-date=2019-05-25|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Torrentfreak/~3/lG8texke7kk/|title=Sweden Asks Advertisers to Blacklist Streaming and Torrent Sites|date=2019-02-23|website=Husham.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nBy April 2019, ISPs in India were ordered to block FMovies,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/pirate-bay-rarbg-1337x-torrentz2-to-be-permanently-blocked-in-india-190412/|title=Pirate Bay, RARBG, 1337x & Torrentz2 to be Permanently Blocked in India|date=2019-04-12|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technadu.com/isps-india-ordered-block-pirate-bay-torrentz2-yts-1337x/64592/|title=ISPs in India Ordered to Block Pirate Bay, Torrentz2, YTS, and 1337x|last=Toulas|first=Bill|date=2019-04-12|website=TechNadu|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techworm.net/2019/04/isp-india-permanently-block-the-pirate-bay-rarbg-1337x-torrentz2.html|title=ISPs in India ordered to permanently block The Pirate Bay, RARBG, 1337x, Torrentz2 and others \u00bb TechWorm|last=techbug9|date=2019-04-13|website=TechWorm|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref> and the U.S. Government identified the site as one of the top piracy sites.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/us-govt-identifies-top-pirate-sites-and-other-notorious-markets-190426/|title=US Govt Identifies Top Pirate Sites and Other 'Notorious Markets'|date=2019-04-26|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technadu.com/ustr-2018-online-piracy-marketplace-list/65995/|title=USTR Released Their 2018 Online Piracy and Marketplace 'Naughty' List|last=Toulas|first=Bill|date=2019-04-27|website=TechNadu|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nAs of November 2019, there are 2 to 4 different FMovies websites running, but their locations are unknown.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Putlocker]], similar online movie streaming network\n* [[YIFY]] Torrents (or YTS Torrents), online movie file downloading network\n* [[Popcorn Time]], a [[freeware]] program allowing users to watch movies through torrenting on several platforms\n* [[123Movies|123movies]], similar online movie streaming network\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\nFmovies Alternative Website\n\n[https://www.bloggingninja.in/fmovies-alternative/ fmovies alternative] \n[[Category:BitTorrent websites]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Piracy website}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name = FMovies\n| logo = FMovies Logo.png\n| logo_size = \n| logo_alt = \n| logo_caption = \n| screenshot = FMovies Homepage Screenshot.jpg\n| collapsible = \n| collapsetext = \n| background = \n| screenshot_size = \n| screenshot_alt = \n| caption = FMovies Homepage as of June 2019\n| url = {{URL|https://www.fmovies.wtf/}}\n| commercial = No\n| type = [[Streaming media|Online Video Streaming]]\n| registration = Yes\n| language = English\n| area_served = Worldwide (blocked in [[Australia]], [[Sweden]] and [[India]])\n| num_users = \n| content_license = \n| programming_language = [[HTML]], [[JavaScript]] and [[PHP]]\n| owner = unknown\n| author = unknown\n| editor = \n| launch_date = {{Start date and age|2016}}\n| revenue = \n| alexa = {{decrease}} 1,063 ({{as of|2020|01|14|alt=January 2020}})<ref name=\"alexa\">{{cite web |url= https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/fmovies.to |title=FMovies.to Site Info |work=[[Alexa Internet|Alexa]] |date=August 2019 |accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n| ip = \n| issn = \n| eissn = \n| oclc = \n| current_status = Online\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''FMovies''' is a series of websites that host links and [[HTML element|embedded videos]], allowing users to stream or download movies for free.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/court-orders-swedish-isp-telia-to-block-the-pirate-bay-181016/|title=Court Orders Swedish ISP Telia to Block The Pirate Bay & FMovies|date=2018-10-16|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/fmovies-loses-control-of-swedish-domain-moves-to-iceland-180907/|title=FMovies Loses Control of Swedish Domain, Moves to Iceland|date=2018-09-07|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/major-pirate-movie-streaming-site-fmovies-sued-in-us-court-161026/|title=Major 'Pirate' Movie Streaming Site Fmovies Sued in US Court|date=2016-10-26|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/us-court-orders-pirate-streaming-site-fmovies-to-pay-210000-170609/|title=US Court Orders Pirate Streaming Site FMovies to Pay $210,000|date=2017-06-09|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe site was created sometime in 2016 according to ''[[TorrentFreak]],''<ref name=\":2\" /> and blocked from [[Google]] searches in December 2016.\n\nIn October 2017, FMovies lost a lawsuit brought by Filipino media and entertainment group [[ABS-CBN]], and was ordered to pay $210,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/abs-cbn-wants-210000-piracy-damages-from-fmovies-170401/|title=ABS-CBN Wants $210,000 Piracy Damages From FMovies|date=2017-04-01|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fossbytes.com/fmovies-shutdown-possible-court-domain-lawsuit/|title=Will FMovies Soon Lose Its Domain Name? Court Orders The Site To Pay $210,000|last=Verma|first=Adarsh|date=2017-06-10|website=Fossbytes|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mobipicker.com/fmovies-copyright-lawsuit/|title=FMovies.to and FMovies.se to Shut Down Soon? US Court Orders To Pay $210,000 In Copyright Infringement Lawsuit|last=Sharma|first=Shubham|date=2017-06-11|website=MobiPicker|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, the site was identified as a ''Notorious Market'' by the U.S. government, along with [[The Pirate Bay]] and other piracy sites.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/us-govt-brands-torrent-streaming-cyberlocker-sites-as-notorious-markets-180115/|title=US Govt Brands Torrent, Streaming & Cyberlocker Sites As Notorious Markets|date=2018-01-15|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, [[Telia Company]], a Swedish ISP, was ordered to block FMovies.<ref name=\":0\" /> They appealed the order.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/swedish-isp-telia-appeals-pirate-bay-blocking-order-181026/|title=Swedish ISP Telia Appeals Pirate Bay Blocking Order|date=2018-10-26|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>  That same month, the [[Motion Picture Association of America]] reported FMovies along with other piracy sites to the U.S. government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/mpaa-reports-notorious-piracy-threats-to-the-us-government-181003/|title=MPAA Reports 'Notorious' Pirate Sites to The US Government|date=2018-10-03|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nFMovies was blocked in Australia in December 2018, after a request in August.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/australian-court-orders-blocking-of-subtitle-piracy-sites/|title=Australian court orders blocking of subtitle piracy sites|last=Barbaschow|first=Asha|website=ZDNet|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/australian-court-orders-isps-to-block-181-pirate-domains-including-subtitle-sites-181220/|title=Australian Court Orders ISPs to Block 181 'Pirate' Domains, Including Subtitle Sites|date=2018-12-20|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/movie-tv-show-companies-want-subtitle-sites-blocked-down-under-180802/|title=Movie & TV Show Companies Want Subtitle Sites Blocked Down Under|date=2018-08-02|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, Sweden asked advertisers to blacklist some piracy and streaming sites, which included FMovies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/sweden-asks-advertisers-to-blacklist-streaming-and-torrent-sites-190223/|title=Sweden Asks Advertisers to Blacklist Streaming and Torrent Sites|date=2019-02-23|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techdoctoruk.com/tech-news/sweden-asks-advertisers-to-blacklist-streaming-and-torrent-sites/|title=Sweden Asks Advertisers to Blacklist Streaming and Torrent Sites \u2013 TechDoctorUK|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://letscrackon.org/sweden-asks-advertisers-to-blacklist-streaming-and-torrent-sites/|title=Sweden Asks Advertisers to Blacklist Streaming and Torrent Sites|last=Tech|first=Free|date=2019-02-23|website=Let's Crack On|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.docsquiffy.com/2019/02/23/sweden-asks-advertisers-to-blacklist-streaming-and-torrent-sites/|title=Sweden Asks Advertisers to Blacklist Streaming and Torrent Sites|last=Squiffy|first=Doc|date=2019-02-23|website=DocSquiffy.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-05-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190525142255/https://www.docsquiffy.com/2019/02/23/sweden-asks-advertisers-to-blacklist-streaming-and-torrent-sites/|archive-date=2019-05-25|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Torrentfreak/~3/lG8texke7kk/|title=Sweden Asks Advertisers to Blacklist Streaming and Torrent Sites|date=2019-02-23|website=Husham.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nBy April 2019, ISPs in India were ordered to block FMovies,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/pirate-bay-rarbg-1337x-torrentz2-to-be-permanently-blocked-in-india-190412/|title=Pirate Bay, RARBG, 1337x & Torrentz2 to be Permanently Blocked in India|date=2019-04-12|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technadu.com/isps-india-ordered-block-pirate-bay-torrentz2-yts-1337x/64592/|title=ISPs in India Ordered to Block Pirate Bay, Torrentz2, YTS, and 1337x|last=Toulas|first=Bill|date=2019-04-12|website=TechNadu|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techworm.net/2019/04/isp-india-permanently-block-the-pirate-bay-rarbg-1337x-torrentz2.html|title=ISPs in India ordered to permanently block The Pirate Bay, RARBG, 1337x, Torrentz2 and others \u00bb TechWorm|last=techbug9|date=2019-04-13|website=TechWorm|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref> and the U.S. Government identified the site as one of the top piracy sites.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/us-govt-identifies-top-pirate-sites-and-other-notorious-markets-190426/|title=US Govt Identifies Top Pirate Sites and Other 'Notorious Markets'|date=2019-04-26|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technadu.com/ustr-2018-online-piracy-marketplace-list/65995/|title=USTR Released Their 2018 Online Piracy and Marketplace 'Naughty' List|last=Toulas|first=Bill|date=2019-04-27|website=TechNadu|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nAs of November 2019, there are 2 to 4 different FMovies websites running, but their locations are unknown.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Putlocker]], similar online movie streaming network\n* [[YIFY]] Torrents (or YTS Torrents), online movie file downloading network\n* [[Popcorn Time]], a [[freeware]] program allowing users to watch movies through torrenting on several platforms\n* [[123Movies|123movies]], similar online movie streaming network\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n[[Category:BitTorrent websites]]\n", "name_user": "Raushankr1100", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(There were some links in this page which I have corrected.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FMovies"}
{"title_page": "Boryspil International Airport", "text_new": "{{for|Kyiv's other international airport inside the city|Kyiv International Airport (Zhuliany)}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| nativename = <small>{{lang|uk|\u041c\u0456\u0436\u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0430\u0435\u0440\u043e\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442 \u00ab\u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441\u043f\u0456\u043b\u044c\u00bb}}</small>\n| location = [[Boryspil]]\n| hub = * [[SkyUp]]\n* {{nowrap|[[Ukraine International Airlines]]}}\n| focus_city = [[Windrose Airlines]]\n| elevation-m = 130\n| metric-elev = Y\n| coordinates = {{coord|50|20|41|N|30|53|36|E|display=inline,title}}\n| r1-length-f = 13,123\n| r1-surface = [[Concrete]]\n| metric-rwy = y\n| name = Boryspil International Airport\n| image = Boryspil International Airport logo (inverted).svg\n| image-width = 250\n| image2 = Aerial of KBP.jpeg\n| image2-width = 250\n| IATA = KBP\n| ICAO = UKBB\n| type = Public/Military\n| owner = \n| operator = Civil Government\n| city-served = [[Kyiv]], [[Ukraine]]\n| elevation-f = 427\n| website = [http://kbp.aero/en/ kbp.aero]\n| pushpin_label = '''KBP'''\n| pushpin_map = Ukraine Kyiv Oblast#Ukraine\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in Kyiv Oblast\n| r1-number = 18L/36R\n| r1-length-m = 4,000\n| r2-number = 18R/36L\n| r2-length-m = 3,500\n| r2-length-f = 11,483\n| r2-surface = [[Concrete]]\n| stat-year = 2019\n| stat1-header = Passengers\n| stat1-data = {{increase}} 15,260,300\n| stat2-header = Flights\n| stat2-data = {{increase}} 110,000\n| footnotes = Source: Official website<ref name=Airport>[http://kbp.com.ua/ukrainian/golovna/index.html Boryspil International Airport] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110806050654/http://kbp.com.ua/ukrainian/golovna/index.html |date=August 6, 2011 }}, official website</ref><br />Ukrainian [[Aeronautical Information Publication|AIP]] at [[European Organisation for the Safety of Air Navigation|EUROCONTROL]]<ref name=\"AIP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ead.eurocontrol.int/publicuser/protect/pu/main.jsp|title=EAD Basic - Error Page|publisher=|accessdate=1 June 2015}}</ref><br />Statistics: Airport Press<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nv.ua/ukr/biz/markets/borispil-aeroport-borispil-zbilshiv-pasazhiropotik-na-21-novini-ukrajini-50063456.html|title=\u0410\u0435\u0440\u043e\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442 \u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441\u043f\u0456\u043b\u044c \u0437\u0430 \u0440\u0456\u043a \u0437\u0431\u0456\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0438\u0432 \u043f\u0430\u0441\u0430\u0436\u0438\u0440\u043e\u043f\u043e\u0442\u0456\u043a \u043d\u0430 21% |publisher=|accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Boryspil International Airport''' ({{lang-uk|\u041c\u0456\u0436\u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0430\u0435\u0440\u043e\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442 \u00ab\u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441\u043f\u0456\u043b\u044c\u00bb}}) {{airport codes|KBP|UKBB}} is an [[international airport]] in [[Boryspil]], {{convert|29|km|abbr=on}} east<ref name=\"AIP\"/> of [[Kyiv]], the capital of Ukraine. It is the country's largest airport, serving 65% of its passenger air traffic, including all its [[Continent|intercontinental]] flights and a majority of international flights.<ref name=IU151013/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.epravda.com.ua/news/2012/08/29/333237/|title=\u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441\u043f\u0456\u043b\u044c \u0432\u0438\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0443\u0454\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f - \u043a\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0443\u0442\u044c \u043d\u0435 \u0432 \u041a\u0438\u0454\u0432\u0456, \u0430 \u0437\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u0434\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c|work=\u0415\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0456\u0447\u043d\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0434\u0430|accessdate=1 June 2015}}</ref> It is one of two passenger airports that serve Kyiv along with the smaller [[Kyiv International Airport (Zhuliany)|Zhulyany Airport]]. Boryspil International Airport is a member of [[Airports Council International]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Early years===\nOn 22 June 1959, the [[Council of Minister]]s of the [[Ukrainian SSR]] ordered the establishment of regular civil air traffic to the then military airfield near Boryspil. On 7 July 1959, the new airport (named Kyiv-Tsentralnyi) received its first scheduled flight. It was [[Aeroflot]]'s [[Tupolev Tu-104]] en route from [[Moscow]], carrying 100 passengers and about 1,600&nbsp;kg of cargo. The first routes served were Moscow\u2013Kyiv-Moscow and [[Saint Petersburg|Leningrad]]\u2013Kyiv\u2013Leningrad.\n\nIn November 1960, the first permanent air group, consisting of Tu-104 and [[Antonov An-10]] planes, was assigned to the airport. Until then it had been served only by aircraft based in Moscow and other cities of the Soviet Union. A new passenger terminal was opened in 1965. Later that year, an automatic landing assistance system was installed.\n\nIn 1963, the Ukrainian Territorial Administration of Civil Aviation formed its Boryspil subdivision consisting of the airport and its air group. The air group grew significantly in the 1960s and 1970s. In 1974 it consisted of four fleets of [[turbojet]] aircraft ([[Tupolev Tu-104|Tu-104]] planes), [[turbofan]] aircraft ([[Tupolev Tu-134|Tu-134]], [[Tupolev Tu-154|Tu-154]] planes) and two fleets of [[turboprop]] aircraft ([[Ilyushin Il-18]] planes).\n\nToward the final decades of the [[Cold War]], the [[Soviet Air Force]] maintained a presence at Boryspil Airport with 1 VTAP (1st Military Aviation Transportation Regiment) flying [[Ilyushin Il-76]] cargo jets.\n\nBy the 1980s, Boryspil had begun receiving limited international flights. Additional passenger services and [[customs]]/[[border control]] groups were established for that purpose. However, ordinary Soviet citizens were not allowed to depart abroad from Kyiv, being restricted to fly only from Moscow airports.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\n===Development since the 1990s===\nIn 1993, the Ministry of Transportation of the newly independent Ukraine reorganized the airport into the Boryspil State International Airport and created a local subdivision of [[Air Ukraine]] to serve it. The airport was opened for any passengers and flights. The number of air and passenger traffic has been growing ever since.\n\nEarly in the 2000s, Boryspil became a hub airport serving destined and transit flights of foreign airlines. Its development strategy stresses the hub role since domestic passenger demand is growing insufficiently compared to the possible transit traffic. In 2001, a new runway was completed, and the airport carried 1.5 million passengers.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://www.sita.aero/content/ukraine%E2%80%99s-largest-airport-selects-sita-reach-18-million-passenger-target-2020|title=SITA - News releases|work=Sita. create success together|accessdate=1 June 2015}}</ref> It is certified for [[Instrument landing system categories|Category III A ILS]] approaches. In 2002 Boryspil airport was certified under the [[ISO 9001]] quality management system.\n\nIt is one of Eastern Europe's largest airports with over 6 million passengers traveling in 2008.<ref>[http://kbp.kiev.ua/ukrainian/pasazhiram/e-6-000-000-pasazhir.html 6 millionth passenger] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090205072029/http://kbp.kiev.ua/ukrainian/pasazhiram/e-6-000-000-pasazhir.html |date=February 5, 2009 }}</ref> It consistently accounted for between 60% and 70% of Ukraine's air travel demand and, despite a drop of 13% in 2009, it handled 5.8 million passengers, more than it handled in 2007.<ref>{{Cite news |work=anna.aero Airline Route News & Analysis |title=Ukraine\u2019s rapid growth faltered in 2009; Kyiv leads recovery in 2010 as Aerosvit and Ukraine International add new routes\n|url=http://www.anna.aero/2010/08/11/ukraines-rapid-growth-faltered-in-2009/ }}</ref>\n\nThe airport survived the [[2012 European cold wave]] without major flight delays or cancellations.<ref>[http://kiev.unian.net/ukr/detail/4131 \u0421\u0442\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0447\u043d\u0456 \u0430\u0435\u0440\u043e\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0446\u044e\u044e\u0442\u044c \u0443 \u0448\u0442\u0430\u0442\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u0440\u0435\u0436\u0438\u043c\u0456] {{in lang|uk}}</ref> According to the media and industry experts, in 2013 once underdog in-city [[Kyiv International Airport (Zhuliany)|Zhulyany Airport]] has rapidly grown into a major, and more efficient, competitor to the still-leading Boryspil Airport.<ref name=\"Kyiv ukhodit v nebo\">{{cite web |url=http://korrespondent.net/business/companies/1556760-korrespondent-kiev-uhodit-v-nebo-aeroport-zhulyany-prevrashchaetsya-v-mladshego-brata-schastlivchika-ne-sli |title=\u041a\u0438\u0435\u0432 \u0443\u0445\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442 \u0432 \u043d\u0435\u0431\u043e. \u0410\u044d\u0440\u043e\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442 \u0416\u0443\u043b\u044f\u043d\u044b \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0440\u0430\u0449\u0430\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0432 \u043c\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0448\u0435\u0433\u043e \u0431\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0430-\u0441\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043b\u0438\u0432\u0447\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u043d\u0435 \u0441\u043b\u0438\u0448\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0443\u0441\u043f\u0435\u0448\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043b\u044f |work=[[Korrespondent]] | date=13 March 2013 |accessdate=24 August 2013 |author=\u0422\u044b\u043c\u043a\u0438\u0432, \u041a\u0430\u0440\u043e\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430}}</ref>\n\n===Ongoing development===\nBoryspil International Airport handles most of Ukraine's international traffic. Terminal B, with only eleven gates, two of which were [[jetway|air bridges]], was not enough to handle all international flights. This was the reason for the expansion of that terminal, which started in 2005. The first-stage expansion of Terminal B was opened on 27 January 2006. In 2008, passport control within Terminal B Departures was moved further east (along with the entrance to the main [[duty-free shop]] so that it remains airside).\n\nThere are plans to expand the airport further by building several new terminals. The government has been having meetings with the owners of nearby land, trying to buy more land for expansion. The construction of Terminal D was approved on 28 July 2008 and was completed in 2012 at a cost of UAH 1.661 billion (US$208 million). The terminal will have a capacity of 1,500 passengers per hour and cover an area of 44.9 hectares.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukranews.com/eng/article/138815.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120917153849/http://www.ukranews.com/eng/article/138815.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=17 September 2012|title=\u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0456 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0438 \u0411\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0435\u0441|accessdate=1 June 2015}}</ref> Platform M, which is connected to Terminal B and requires redevelopment, was to be reconstructed in 2009-2010. The reason for the delay in its reconstruction was the fact that Terminal B needs to be fully operational first. Now that Terminal D has opened (building began on 24 October 2008<ref name=\"D\">{{cite web|url=http://photo.unian.net/eng/themes/9871|title=Start of terminal \"D\" building at the airport \"Borispol\"|publisher=|accessdate=1 June 2015}}</ref>), platform M can be reconstructed without having a major impact on traffic.\n\nThe construction of Terminal D was completed in 2012, with the terminal opening to passengers on 28 May 2012, increasing passenger handling facilities significantly. As of June 24, 2016, Terminal A, B, and F are out of operation. By 2020, if all plans proceed, the airport should have a capacity of 18 million passengers per year.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n==Terminals and infrastructure==\n===Terminals===\nBoryspil International Airport has one operational passenger terminals (D), one cargo terminal (F) and a VIP terminal. The largely overcrowded former domestic Terminal A was closed on 15 September 2011, in favor of transferring all domestic operations to nearby Terminal B. In 2013, all domestic and international operations were transferred from Terminal B to Terminal D.\n\n==== Terminal B ====\n[[File:Borispol B terminal.jpg|thumb|Terminal B]]\nTerminal B, the original Soviet-constructed building, used to serve domestic and international flights. It has undergone extensive, long-term reconstruction. The terminal hosted shops, cafes, travel agencies and banks, as well as offices of airlines and a business center. The ground floor features luggage storage, waiting-area, and check-in desks, whilst security and passport (immigration) control, the main departure lounge and the terminal's boarding gates are on the second floor. After passport control, passengers wait in the departure lounge where there is a business lounge, a number of cafes, restaurants and duty-free shops. There is free [[Wireless Internet|Wi-Fi access]] in the building.<ref>[https://www.kyiv-airport.com/kyiv-boryspil/terminal-b.php kyiv-airport.com - Kyiv Borispol Airport Terminal B] retrieved 20 June 2018</ref> The terminal has two [[jetbridge]]s and several bus-boarding stands. It is now used for charter flights for Hasidic Pilgrims participating in [[Rosh Hashanah kibbutz]] in Ukraine.\n\n==== Terminal D ====\n[[File:Boryspil_Terminal_D_check-in.JPG|thumb|Interior of Terminal D]]\nTerminal D, construction of which began on 24 March 2008,<ref name=\"D\"/> was opened on 28 May 2012 with an initial capacity of 3,100 passengers per hour.<ref name=\"korrespondent.net\">{{cite web|author1=Design by Maxim Tkachuk |author2=web-architecture by Volkova Dasha |author3=Yuriy Sokolov |author4=templated by Alexey Kovtanets |author5=programming by Irina Batvina |author6=Maxim Bielushkin |author7=Sergey Bogatyrchuk |author8=Borshchanenko Maksym |author9=Vitaliy Galkin |author10=Victor Lushkin |author11=Dmitry Medun |author12=Igor Sitnikov |author13=Vladimir Tarasov |author14=Alexander Filippov |author15=Sergei Koshelev |author16=Yaroslav Ostapiuk |author17=Viktor Voitenko |url=http://korrespondent.net/business/companies/1353920-ukrainskie-i-mezhdunarodnye-aviakompanii-perejdut-na-obsluzhivanie-v-terminal-d-s-1-avgusta |title=\u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0438 \u043c\u0435\u0436\u0434\u0443\u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0430\u0432\u0438\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0439\u0434\u0443\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0438\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0432 \u0442\u0435\u0440\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043b D \u0441 1 \u0430\u0432\u0433\u0443\u0441\u0442\u0430 \u00bb \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0438 \u0437\u0430\u0440\u0443\u0431\u0435\u0436\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u2013 \u041a\u043e\u0440\u0440\u0435\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043d\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442 |publisher=Korrespondent.net |date=2012-05-28 |accessdate=2012-10-25}}</ref> It received its first arrivals passengers on 29 May 2012.\n\nTerminal D serves domestic and international flights. It is also a hub and a home base of [[Ukraine International Airlines]]. It has been designed to support an integrated system for monitoring and directing arriving and departing passengers; this has been ensured by implementing a scheme of movement based on the principle of multi-level zoning \u2014 departing passengers use the airport's upper floors, whilst those arriving and yet to pass through immigration are processed on a lower level. The ground and first floors are used for airside service and the sorting of baggage. Airside, the first floor is used for arrivals zone and baggage hall. The fourth floor is reserved for airlines' lounges. The terminal can be accessed from the airport's central access road for arrivals and in the same way but via a ramp for departures level. The building features both [[jetbridge]]s and bus boarding stands and is equipped to handle wide-body aircraft such as Ukraine International Airlines' [[Boeing 777-200ER]]s.\n\nThe [[State Border Service of Ukraine|Ukrainian Border Guard]] and State Customs Service maintain control points for arriving and departing passengers (40 passport booths for arrivals and 28 for departures). The terminal has 11 gates equipped with jetways and additional 'bus gates'.\n\nTerminal D regularly features [[Ukrainian art]] exhibitions by such notables as [[Maria Prymachenko]] and [[Yuriy Khimich]], organised by the art fund \"Artaniya\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/ukraine/kyiv-post/20151127/281767038139920|title=PressReader.com - Connecting People Through News|website=www.pressreader.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://day.kyiv.ua/en/article/time-out/gallery-national-pride |title=\"The Gallery of National Pride\" &#124; The Day newspaper |publisher=Day.kyiv.ua |date=2013-06-04 |accessdate=2018-08-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://uacrisis.org/55365-diyachi-ukrayini-3|title=An exhibition Prominent Ukrainians opens in Kyiv International Airport - UACRISIS.ORG|date=18 April 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==== Terminal F ====\n[[File:\u0410\u044d\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0440\u043e\u043c\u044b_\u0438_\u0442\u0435\u0440\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044b-\u0442\u0435\u0440\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043b,_\u041a\u0438\u0435\u0432_-_\u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043b\u044c_RP94559.jpg|thumb|Terminal F]]\nTerminal F is a passenger terminal mostly used by low-cost carriers and was opened on 21 September 2010 as a home base for [[Ukraine International Airlines]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/news/city/detail/83206/|title=Yanukovych opens new terminal at Boryspil Airport - Sep. 21, 2010|date=21 September 2010|publisher=}}</ref> Terminal F started handling regular flights as of 31 October 2010, with an initial capacity of 900 passengers/hour.<ref>[http://www.kbp.com.ua/english/for-passengers/31-zhovtnya-2010-r.-z-terminalu-f-pochnut-zdiysnyuvatisya-mizhnarodni-reysi.html Since October 31, 2010, International Flights to be Operated Through Terminal F] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101023092353/http://www.kbp.com.ua/english/for-passengers/31-zhovtnya-2010-r.-z-terminalu-f-pochnut-zdiysnyuvatisya-mizhnarodni-reysi.html |date=October 23, 2010 }}, [[Kyiv Post]] (August 11, 2010)</ref> The terminal is not equipped with jetways as it was originally meant to serve low-cost airlines. However, the higher level of service offered led to the transfer of many scheduled European and Asian carriers to the terminal.\n\nThe opening of Terminal F greatly reduced the overcrowding at Terminal B, which had previously been Boryspil's only operating international terminal. Upon opening of Terminal F and expansion/reconfiguration of Terminal B's airside departures to serve domestic flights, the airport was able to close the largely outdated domestic Terminal A.\n\nTerminal used to serve [[UTair-Ukraine]], [[airBaltic]], [[Adria Airways]], [[Armavia]], [[Austrian Airlines]], [[Belavia]], [[British Airways]], [[LOT Polish Airlines]], [[Georgian Airways]], [[Germanwings]], [[Libyan Airlines]], [[Lufthansa]], [[Finnair]], [[KLM]], [[S7 Airlines]], [[Turkish Airlines]] and others. All of them were transferred to Terminal D. Ukraine International Airlines transferred all of its regular flights to Terminal D on 30 May 2013 but UIA's charter flights stayed in Terminal F. It was expected that Terminal F would be also used for [[low-cost carrier]]s. In October 2013, the terminal was used for charter flights and low-cost airlines; it serviced three or four, sometimes eight, flights a day.<ref name=IU151013>[http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/economic/170435.html Terminal F of Boryspil airport to become cargo terminal] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220164011/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/economic/170435.html |date=2015-02-20 }}, [[Interfax-Ukraine]] (15 October 2013)</ref> On 15 October airport management decided that terminal F will be used as a cargo terminal in the future.<ref name=IU151013/> On 27 October 2013, all flights were transferred from terminal F to terminal D.<ref name=IU151013/>\n\nTerminal F was reopened on 31 March 2019, and is used as a passenger facility for low-cost carriers, especially [[Ryanair]].<ref>[https://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/news/70778-kiev-boryspil-to-reopen-terminal-f-for-ryanair] 11 September 2018</ref> The following airlines have confirmed their move to Terminal F: [[Ryanair]], [[Laudamotion]], [[Yanair]], [[Bravo Airways]], [[Iraqi Airways]], [[SkyUp]], [[Aigle Azur]] and [[Air Serbia]].<ref>[https://www.avianews.com/ukraine/2019/03/25/borispol_terminal_f_100mln/] 25 March 2019</ref>\n\n=== Infrastructure ===\nBoryspil airport has two [[runway]]s, with the terminals occupying a center-field location.\n\n* The eastern No. 1 runway (36R-18L) built in 2001 serves majority of flights.\n* The western No. 2 runway (36L-18R).\n\nIn the long term, there are plans to build a third [[crosswind]] runway.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kreschatic.kiev.ua/ru/3454/news/1278498509.html |title=\u0412 \u0430\u044d\u0440\u043e\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0443 \"\u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043b\u044c\" \u043f\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0440\u0435\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u043a\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0439 \u0432\u0437\u043b\u0435\u0442\u043d\u043e-\u043f\u043e\u0441\u0430\u0434\u043e\u0447\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0441\u044b, - \u041a.\u0415\u0444\u0438\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e &#124; \u0425\u0440\u0435\u0449\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043a - \u041a\u0438\u0457\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u043c\u0443\u043di\u0446\u0438\u043f\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430 \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 |publisher=Kreschatic.kiev.ua |date= |accessdate=2012-10-25}}</ref>\n\nShort-stay car parking facilities at are provided in the immediate vicinity of terminals B and F, whilst long term parking facilities are in the vicinity of the airport's access road and 'station square'. In addition to these facilities, the airport is, in connection with the construction of Terminal D, building its first [[multi-storey car park]]; this will be a combined long- and short-stay car park.\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n===Passenger===\nThe following airlines offer regular scheduled and charter services to and from  Boryspil International Airport:<ref>[https://kbp.aero/en/seasonal-schedule-of-the-international-airport-borispol/ kbp.aero - SEASONAL SCHEDULE OF THE INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT BORISPOL] retrieved 4 December 2017</ref>\n\n{{Airport destination list\n<!-- -->\n|[[Aegean Airlines]] | [[Athens International Airport|Athens]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Air Arabia]] | [[Sharjah International Airport|Sharjah]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Air Astana]] | [[Almaty International Airport|Almaty]], [[Nursultan Nazarbayev International Airport|Nur-Sultan]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[airBaltic]] | [[Riga International Airport|Riga]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Air France]] | '''Seasonal:''' [[Charles de Gaulle Airport|Paris\u2013Charles de Gaulle]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Air France \u043d\u0430 \u0437\u0438\u043c\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0441\u0435\u0437\u043e\u043d \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0442 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442\u044b \u0432 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0443 {{!}} avianews.com |url=https://www.avianews.com/ukraine/2019/05/22/af_kiev_paris_winter2019/ |accessdate=22 May 2019 |date=22 May 2019 |language=ru-RU}}</ref>\n<!-- -->    \n|[[Air Malta]] | [[Malta International Airport|Malta]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Liu|first1=Jim|title=airmalta resumes Kyiv service from June 2018|url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/278184/airmalta-resumes-kiev-service-from-june-2018/|accessdate=18 April 2018|work=Routesonline|date=18 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Air Malta to add a new route to Kyiv|url=https://worl